<font color="#FF0000">MICHAEL HERR</font><br>
<tt>Thu May 15 11:45:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I believe Michael Herr may have done more to shape American civilian perception of the Vietnam war than any other writer.  From his Esquire articles published during the war, to his fine book &quot;Dispatches&quot; published shortly after American involvement ended, to Captain Willard's soliloquies in &quot;Apocalypse Now&quot; and his heavy involvement with &quot;Full Metal Jacket&quot; (both of which featured scenes and dialogue lifted straight out of &quot;Dispatches&quot;), he's been sort of a media triple-threat whose view of the war has become sort of pervasive.  Not being a vet, I can't judge how realistic his  portrayals are; but having read and seen many of them as a civilian, I can tell you this -- his views, in large part, became substitute experience for those of us who weren't there.
